highlights.description: Spoke about the intersection of race and class and how growing up poor looks different now compared to in the '80s.
Hawk expressing what it means for a group of white people to be talking about issues impacting Communities of Color.
Bob talking about finding common ground among difference
East High graduate's reflections on Principal McPike

Being white and poor in the 80's in Madison was manageable in the sense that her family never went hungry and was assisted by welfare. She is not sure how being poor and any other identity may be manageable today.
People rarely talk to each other nowadays.
She used to be afraid of black Americans because she barely interacted with them.
Students in "progressive" Madison were attacked with tear gas for their advocacy against the Vietnam War.
Racism continues to be an issue in Madison.

The value of respect is not as followed in todays day and age. --> Update: I thought this was important to listen to because despite growing up between two cultures, the concept of respect towards elders was always central to our upbringing.  It seems that some youth today have lost this value.
Black and brown families experience racism often.  If people want to know what they've been through they should ask them.  It is powerful to have ethno-racial representation in positions of power.
People should listen to each other and be sensitive to their life experiences.
Bob's comment that schools need to expect children to respect others
Bob and Sabrina commenting on the need to have these conversations to understand each others' experiences
